                                            </head>
                                            <div type="positioning">
                                                <p>
                                                    <geo>30.05, 31.233333</geo>
                                                </p>
                                            </div>
                                            <div type="typology">
                                                <p>Eastern › Egyptian › Central Delta</p>
                                                <p>Urban, sedentary, high prestige variety</p>
                                            </div>
                                            <div type="general">
                                                <p>The Egyptian varieties of Arabic form a quite diversified linguistic group.
               They are usually subdivided into four major subgroups: the dialects of Upper Egypt,
               Middle Egypt, Lower Egypt and those spoken in the Oases.
               The dialect of the capital belongs to the northern group.</p>
                                                <p>By contrast to most other varieties of vernacular Arabic, the dialect of Cairo
               has been reduced to writing as well. There exists quite a significant amount of
               literary output, in particular stage plays.</p>
                                            </div>
                                            <div type="researchHistory">
                                                <p>
                                                    The first serious reliable descriptions of Egyptian Arabic
were written in the 19th century: Wilhelm Spitta published his
                                                    <ref target="vicav_bibl_002|id==spitta_bey_wilhelm_001">grammar in 1880</ref>
                                                    (which
can be
                                                    <ref target="https://archive.org/details/grammatikdesara00spitgoog">read 
online at the Internet Archive</ref>
                                                    ) and Vollers a
                                                    <ref target="vicav_bibl_002|id==vollers_karl_001">textbook in 
1890</ref>
                                                    (
                                                    <ref target="vicav_bibl_002|id==vollers_karl_002">English translation 1895</ref>
                                                    , available at the
                                                    <ref target="https://archive.org/details/cu31924026886816">Internet 
Archive</ref>
                                                    ). These were followed by
                                                    <ref target="vicav_bibl_002|id==nallino_1900a">Nallino (1900)</ref>
                                                    (full text at the
                                                    <ref target="https://archive.org/details/laraboparlatoine00nalluoft">Internet Archive</ref>
                                                    ) and
                                                    <ref target="vicav_bibl_002|id==willmore_1901a">Willmore (1905)</ref>
                                                    (full text at the
                                                    <ref target="https://archive.org/details/cu31924026887152">Internet Archive</ref>
                                                    ).
                                                </p>
                                                <p>
                                                    The great bulk of publications was written after World War II. Interesting information was
provided by
                                                    <ref target="vicav_bibl_002|id==mitchell_t_f_001">Mitchell (1956)</ref>
                                                    ,
                                                    <ref target="vicav_bibl_002|id==tomiche_nada_001">Tomiche (1962)</ref>
                                                    and
                                                    <ref target="vicav_bibl_002|id==salib_m_b_001">Salib (1981)</ref>
                                                    .
Most studies followed rather traditional approaches. An exception is
                                                    <ref target="vicav_bibl_002|id==wise_hillary_001">Wise’s transformational grammar
(1975)</ref>
                                                    . Another very informative monography is Parkinson’s socio-linguistic study on
                                                    <ref target="vicav_bibl_002|id==parkinson_d_b_001">terms of address in Egyptian Arabic (1985)</ref>
                                                    .
                                                </p>
                                                <p>
                                                    The most substantial scholarly contributions to our knowledge of the Egyptian dialects
were made by the German dialectologists Behnstedt and Woidich. Most of their work was done 
in the 80’s and 90’s of the 20th century. Woidich’s
                                                    <ref target="vicav_bibl_002|id==Woidich_2006a">grammar (2006) of Cairo 
Arabic</ref>
                                                    is the so far most comprehensive in-depth study of this variety.
                                                </p>
                                            </div>
                                            <div type="sampleText">
                                                <p>
                                                    A short sample text with POS and translations of lemmas is provided
                                                    <ref target="vicav_sampletexts|sampleText==cairo_sample_01">here</ref>
                                                    .
                                                </p>
                                            </div>
                                            <div type="bibliography">
                                                <p>
                                                    Until the late twentieth century, the language of the Egyptian capital
            remained poorly documented. Meanwhile, a number of valuable descriptions 
            have been published. The amount of literature is quite considerable.
                                                    <ptr target="vicav_bibl_002|vicavTaxonomy=Cairo"/>
                                                </p>
                                            </div>
                                            <div type="textBooks">
                                                <p>
                                                    For generations of learners of spoken Egyptian the course material
compiled by Abdel-Massih (1978-9) was the main guidance. A more up-to-date textbook is 
Woidich/Heinen’s
                                                    <ref target="vicav_bibl_002|id==woidich_heinen_2004a">Kullu tamām! (2004)</ref>
                                                    . 
Furthermore, a graded series of textbooks by
                                                    <ref target="vicav_bibl_002|author=Louis, Samia">Samia Louis</ref>
                                                    has to be mentioned. In 
these books, all the reading material is presented in the Arabic script. In addition, they come with high quality CDs.
                                                </p>
                                                <p>
                                                    Two German textbooks should also be highlighted: Woidich’s
                                                    <ref target="vicav_bibl_002|id==woidich_ahlan_2002">Ahlan wa Sahlan (2002)</ref>
                                                    actually predates his Kullu tamām!. The sesond one is Ahmed’s
                                                    <ref target="vicav_bibl_002|id==ahmed_mokhtar_001">Lehrbuch 
des Ägyptisch-Arabischen (1981)</ref>
                                                    which unfortunately contains 
countless typos. Nevertheless, the texts collected there are very helpful, especially for 
advanced learners.
                                                </p>
                                            </div>
                                            <div type="dictionaries">
                                                <p>
                                                    There exist several dictionaries for those who want to study Egyptian Arabic.
   The hitherto most comprehensive one is
                                                    <ref target="vicav_bibl_002|id==hinds_martin_001">Hinds/Badawi (Arabic-English)</ref>
                                                    . It was published 
   in 1986.
                                                </p>
                                                <p>
                                                    Our site provides a small digital dictionary of Cairo Arabic.
   It primarily serves didactic purposes. You can access it
                                                    <ref target="arz_eng_006">here</ref>
                                                    .
                                                </p>
                                                <p>
                                                    <ref target="vicav_bibl_002|id==spiro_001">Socrates Spiro’s dictionary (1895)</ref>
                                                    is pretty old.
As there is not much available in digital form, it is still worth looking at. To access it
                                                    <ref target="http://archive.org/details/anarabicenglish00spirgoog">click here</ref>
                                                    .
                                                </p>
                                                <p>
                                                    To obtain a list of Egyptian dictionaries contained in our database
                                                    <ref target="vicav_bibl_002|vicavTaxonomy=lexicon">click here</ref>
                                                    .
                                                </p>
